<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-comparing-distributions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Comparing the Distributions</title>
  <p>
    Having explored these distributions individually, it is useful to compare their shapes. The Normal and <m>t</m> distributions 
    are both symmetric and bell-shaped, although the <m>t</m> distribution has heavier tails, particularly for small degrees of freedom. 
    In contrast, the Chi-square and <m>F</m> distributions are positively skewed and take only positive values.
  </p>
  <p>
    Although these distributions appear different, they are mathematically related. Many statistical procedures begin by assuming 
    that the data are approximately Normally distributed. From this assumption arise the <m>t</m>, Chi-square and <m>F</m> distributions, 
    which provide the basis for many statistical tests introduced later in this book.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can investigate these relationships further by using the same <em>Show Model</em> dialog to display each distribution in turn. 
    Because the dialog uses a common interface for all probability distributions, it is easy to compare their shapes by changing only the 
    selected distribution and its parameters.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig-variaterelations">
    <caption>
      Comparison of the Normal, <m>t</m>, Chi-square and <m>F</m> distributions. Although their shapes differ, 
      these distributions are closely related and form the basis of many inferential statistical methods.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/variaterelations.png"/>
  </figure>  
</subsection>